1517–Deceased","1519–1584":"1519–1584","–Female":"Deceased","1535–1614":"1535–1614","1489–1543":"1489–1543","1490–1541":"1490–1541","1570":"1570","1490":"1490","1513":"1513","1535":"1535","15 August 1543":"15 August 1543","1546":"1546","1557":"1557","1512":"1512","1489":"1489","1543":"1543","1510":"1510","1541":"1541","1584":"1584","about 1510":"about 1510","1519":"1519","1517":"1517","1614":"1614","1515":"1515","Westminster, Middlesex, , England":"Westminster, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Sturton le Steeple, Nottinghamshire, England":"Sturton le Steeple, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robinson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Robin  , a pet form of   Robert  , + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Robin  .","West Indian (including Haiti) and Guyanese: most likely not (only) of English or French origin as in 1 above and 2 above, but also, if not mostly, from the related name of the famous Daniel Defoe's literary character <i>Robinson Crusoe</i> (from a novel first published in 1719)."],"variants":[{"name":"Robbinson","meanings":["Altered form of English or French   Robinson  ."]},{"name":"Robin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Emile, Marcel, Achille, Armand, Arnaud, Camille, Julien, Michel, Normand.","French, Breton, Scottish, English, and German: from the personal name <i>Robin</i>, a pet form of   Robert  , composed of the short form <i>Rob</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-in</i>.","Slovenian: topographic name derived from <i>rob</i> ‘edge, border’ (see   Robar  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Robinson was born in 1513, in Westminster, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Robinson, was 24 and his mother, Anne Agnes Savage, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Jane Kaffe. He died in 1546, in his hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1513–1546":"1513–1546","1510–1557":"1510–1557","1512–1570":"1512–1570","1515–Female":"1515–Surnud","1517–Female":"1517–Surnud","1519–1584":"1519–1584","–Female":"Surnud","1535–1614":"1535–1614","1489–1543":"1489–1543","1490–1541":"1490–1541","1570":"1570","1490":"1490","1513":"1513","1535":"1535","15 August 1543":"15. august 1543","1546":"1546","1557":"1557","1512":"1512","1489":"1489","1543":"1543","1510":"1510","1541":"1541","1584":"1584","about 1510":"umbes 1510","1519":"1519","1517":"1517","1614":"1614","1515":"1515","Westminster, Middlesex, , England":"Westminster, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sturton le Steeple, Nottinghamshire, England":"Sturton le Steeple, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1513–1546":"1513–1546","1510–1557":"1510–1557","1512–1570":"1512–1570","1515–Female":"1515–Kuollut","1517–Female":"1517–Kuollut","1519–1584":"1519–1584","–Female":"Kuollut","1535–1614":"1535–1614","1489–1543":"1489–1543","14